'''John Shirley-Quirk''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 28 August 1931) is an English [[bass-baritone]].

He was born in [[Liverpool]], [[England]], and sang in his high school choir. He played the violin and was awarded a scholarship. While studying chemistry and physics at [[Liverpool University]], he studied voice with [[Austen Carnegie]].

He made his operatic debut in [[Debussy]]'s [[Pell<U+00E9>as et M<U+00E9>lisande (opera)|Pell<U+00E9>as et M<U+00E9>lisande]] at the [[Glyndebourne Festival]] in [[1961]], and has been prominent in performing and recording the vocal works of [[Benjamin Britten]]. These have included the premiere performances of ''Canticle IV: Journey of the Magi'' and ''[[Death in Venice (opera)|Death in Venice]]''. The latter part was written specially for him, and involves multiple roles as antagonist to the character of Gustav von Aschenbach. In [[1977]] he created the role of Lev in Sir [[Michael Tippett]]<U+2019>s ''The Ice Break'' at [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]].

He appears regularly with major orchestras and opera companies throughout the world and has a vast discography. Notable recordings include Britten's works and [[Mahler|Mahler's]] [[Symphony No. 8 (Mahler)|Eighth Symphony]] under Sir [[Georg Solti]] on [[Decca Records|Decca]], and [[Ralph Vaughan Williams|Vaughan Williams']] vocal works under Sir [[David Willcocks]] and the [[Choir of King's College, Cambridge]] for [[EMI]].

In [[1975]], John Shirley-Quirk was made a Commander of the Order of the British Empire.

He was a member of staff at [[Acton, London|Acton]] Technical College until [[1957]] and played a part in events leading to the formation of [[Brunel University|Brunel College]]. He is currently on the faculty of the [[Peabody Institute|Peabody Conservatory of Music]] in Baltimore, MD.

Shirley-Quirk was married to [[oboe|oboist]] Sara Watkins, who died in 1997.

